# TaskMaster Integration Rules

ALWAYS use TaskMaster for task management instead of informal checklists:

## Quick Reference Commands
```bash
# View tasks: task-master list [--status=pending|done|in-progress]
# Add task: task-master add-task --prompt="Task description" --priority=high|medium|low
# Update status: task-master set-status --id=N --status=done|in-progress|pending|cancelled
# Show details: task-master show N
# Add subtask: task-master add-subtask --parent=N --title="Subtask" --description="Details"
# Update task: task-master update-task --id=N --prompt="New info"
# Remove task: task-master remove-task --id=N -y
# Next task: task-master next
```

## Task Creation Rules
When creating tasks, ALWAYS include:
- üìã Checkboxes `- [ ]` for subtasks and action items  
- üéØ Emojis for visual clarity (ADHD-friendly)
- üìå Clear headings and subheadings
- ‚úÖ Specific acceptance criteria

Example task description:
```
## üéØ Main Goal
Brief overview of what needs to be done

### üìã Action Items
- [ ] First concrete step
- [ ] Second step with details
- [ ] Third step

### ‚ö° Technical Requirements
- [ ] Requirement 1
- [ ] Requirement 2

### ‚úÖ Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Tests pass
- [ ] Documentation updated
- [ ] Code reviewed
```

## Working with Tasks
1. **Start of session**: Run `task-master list --status=pending` to see what's active
2. **Before starting work**: Update status with `task-master set-status --id=N --status=in-progress`
3. **Track progress**: Use `task-master update-task --id=N --prompt="Progress update"`
4. **Complete work**: Mark done with `task-master set-status --id=N --status=done`

## Important Notes
- TaskMaster persists between sessions (unlike markdown checklists)
- Bash history is limited (~1000 lines) - TaskMaster keeps permanent record
- Use task IDs in commit messages for traceability
- Update tasks immediately after completing work

